In theory, that should not happen. The logic is there to handle this case (I think!). Let me try reproing via shape inference tests.

Let's assume the you have 1D input of shape [10]. For start = -1, end = -INT_MAX, step = -1.

The code snippets are from the shape inferencing logic in ONNX - 

```
            // process start
            auto start = starts[axis_index];
            if (start < 0)
              start += input_dim_value;
            if (step < 0)
              start = clamp(start, 0, input_dim_value - 1);
            else
              start = clamp(start, 0, input_dim_value);
```
 start should now be *corrected* to 9 (-1 + 10 = 9)
 
```
            // process end
            auto end = ends[axis_index];
            if (end < 0)
              end += input_dim_value;
            if (step < 0)
              end = clamp(end, -1, input_dim_value);
            else
              end = clamp(end, 0, input_dim_value);
```
end will now be clamped to -1 (step is negative).

output_dim = (end - start) / step = (-1 - 9)/ -1 = 10.

The logic (even in current state) should handle this. Let me take a look.

I added a test as suggested by you to try and repro your suggested case in the previous comment: start = -1, end = -INT_MAX, step = -1 with initializers and it works as expected - 

```
TEST(SliceTest, Slice1D_ReverseAllAxes_WithInitializers_ToTriggerShapeInferencing) {
  OpTester testv10("Slice", 10);
  testv10.AddInput<float>("data", {4}, {1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f, 4.0f});
  testv10.AddInput<int64_t>("starts", {1}, {-1}, true);                           // make 'starts' an initializer
  testv10.AddInput<int64_t>("ends", {1}, {-std::numeric_limits<int32_t>::max()}, true);  // make 'ends' an initializer
  testv10.AddInput<int64_t>("axes", {1}, {0}, true);                              // make 'axes' an initializer
  testv10.AddInput<int64_t>("steps", {1}, {-1}, true);                           // make 'steps' an initializer
  testv10.AddOutput<float>("output", {4}, {4.0f, 3.0f, 2.0f, 1.0f});
  testv10.Run(OpTester::ExpectResult::kExpectSuccess, "", {kTensorrtExecutionProvider});
}
```

To me the only divergence between ORT and ONNX shape inference will be the case you described in  the issue description - "INT_MAX is used for end, while -1 for start, with -1 for step". ORT special cases INT_MAX and handles this for `step = -1` (superfluously maybe as this is not explicitly mentioned in the spec), whereas ONNX doesn't special-case INT_MAX at all. This should be the only divergence and if spec is clarified appropriately, we don't need to change anything in the ONNX shape inference. Please correct me if I am wrong.
